According to Li et al. and Golmohammadzadeh et al., at high temperature, the reaction with citric
acid was chemically controlled for Li, Co, Ni, and Mn [104,190]. However, kinetics curves from the
shrinking core model shown by Li et al. deviated from linearity during the first 4 to 8 min for Co, Ni,
and Mn between 50 °C and 80 °C. The reaction could instead follow a two-step mechanism for
transition metals. Interestingly, Chen et al. replaced H
by green tea waste, reaching similar
leaching efficiencies for both reducing agents (from 96% to 99%). Although the residue of green tea
provided attractive leaching results and allowed reclamation of an industrial waste, this process may
be difficult to apply at a larger scale due to difficulties related to reducing agent dosage. The authors
did not provide a method to quantify the reductive power of the green tea waste, although they
suggested a mechanism for the oxidation reaction.
